        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: NightSpirit</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 19, 2009<br><br>We do believe that Jesus gave gifts and offices to the church as in 2 Corinthians 12 and we respect those offices and the people who serve others who may be weak in faith or in a crisis. <br><br>--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br><br>1 Corinthians 12:28 - And God hath set some in the church, first apostles, secondarily prophets, thirdly teachers, after that miracles, then gifts of healings, helps, governments, diversities of tongues<br><br>Ephesians 4:11 - And he gave some, apostles; and some, prophets; and some, evangelists; and some, pastors and teachers;   <br><br>--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>So a protestant who doesn't feel at peace with God concerning sin does have available to them spiritual help and counsel from other Christians, pastors, teachers, etc. <br><br>I understand why Catholics believe as they do, that Peter was ordained by Jesus to establish a new organization, with priests and rituals, as earthly points of contact with Jesus. I have no problem with that because I believe those things may be physical expressions that convey the same underlying spiritual principles, that is, it is ultimately our faith in the power of Jesus to cleanse and forgive us that saves us.  <br><br>I would be willing to go more into why Protestants do not feel they need a priest or a Pope, along with supporting biblical references but I don't think this is the thread for it, since that is more of a debate. <br><br>But I get your point, that you believe a person with an absolution from a priest, because of the belief in the priest as a representitive of Christ, can have a more physical assurance of salvation than a protestant. <br><br>Whereas, protestants have faith that Jesus hears us and sees the intent of our hearts when we confess directly to Him and we accept His forgiveness by faith. We place our confidence in the Bible, which says this is true. And we also have confidence in the power of God's spirit to guide each of us individually, as sons, and to bear witness with our spirit that we are forgiven.</span>
