        June 19, 2009<br><br>I think you are correct that God's nature doesn't change but I believe His methods or symbols, have and do change. <br><br>Briefly, protestants feel that the purpose of the temple was to offer blood sacrifices and were established as foretelling of Christ. When Christ came and was sacrificed, as the lamb of God, protestants believe the purpose of the temple and the priesthood was fulfilled so they are no longer needed. When the veil of the temple was torn asunder supernaturally after the crucifixation, we see that as symobolic of the end of any separation or mediator needed between God and man, except Jesus. The protestant term used is the &quot;priesthood of the believer&quot; which is based on their interpretation of the new covenant.<br><br>--------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>Hebrews 8: 7-11<br><br>7 For if that first covenant had been faultless, then should no place have been sought for the second. <br><br>8 For finding fault with them, he saith, Behold, the days come, saith the Lord, when I will make a new covenant with the house of Israel and with the house of Judah: <br><br>9 Not according to the covenant that I made with their fathers in the day when I took them by the hand to lead them out of the land of Egypt; because they continued not in my covenant, and I regarded them not, saith the Lord.<br><br><br>10 For this is the covenant that I will make with the house of Israel after those days, saith the Lord; I will put my laws into their mind, and write them in their hearts: and I will be to them a God, and they shall be to me a people: <br><br>11 And they shall not teach every man his neighbour, and every man his brother, saying, Know the Lord: for all shall know me, from the least to the greatest. <br><br>--------------------------------------------------------------------------</span>
