        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: Rev. Brandon A. Olivares</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 18, 2009<br><br>I think the question in this thread still stands though.<br><br>I was thinking that God has always provided some physical representation. Remember the pillar of cloud and of fire that God used to lead the Jews? And how exact God was about the specifications of the temple, and about the ritual around that temple, e.g., only the priest being able to go into certain areas. And the physical representation of the Jews' sins, atoned by sacrifice, also as a pointer to the perfect sacrifice that would soon come. Also, he always appointed a lead profit or king to lead the Jews.<br><br>God's nature does not change, so it makes sense to me that he would have similar physical representations today.<br><br>In terms of knowing one is saved, well I think to confession, where there's a physical representation to assure one of one's forgiveness, because it is actually spoken. Jesus left 2,000 years ago, but he left us a line of bishops, in order to guide us, just as the apostles were the driving force behind the Church 2,000 years ago. There are many other parallels I see, but they aren't really related to this thread.<br><br>God knows that we are physical beings, and it is a lot easier for us to have faith when he deals in the physical as well. That's the whole idea behind the sacraments, I think.<br><br>Those are only my thoughts, and would be curious what others think.</span>
