        June 9, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by <strong>NightSpirit</strong></div><br><br>I don't think the Bible specifies whether salvation has to happen instantly or whether we can also come to believe gradually, through observations and studying the Bible.</blockquote><br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by Okoit B. Etyang</div><br><br>I beg to disagree with your opinion; it is well defined in the Bible on how one receives salvation and then lives a life of salvation and finally maintains the same and here are the verses to prove that;</blockquote><br><br>So you are of the opinion that salvation is not an event but a process? That we are not really completely &quot;saved&quot; until we have endured until the end? If you are saying that salvation consist of a beginning event, a continuing process and an concluding event that sounds alright to me. <br><br>My point was that salvation is taught by many protestants as a one-time event, leaving many to doubt their salvation if that beginning event was not as dramatic or the same as someone else's experience. <br><br><blockquote>For it is by grace you have been saved, through faith&#8212;and this not from yourselves, it is the gift of God. EPHESIANS 2:8</blockquote><br><br>The key words here I would like you to notice is &quot;have been.&quot; A gift of which we then have to earn the remainder? Or a gift that is being held in trust until we show we have been worthy of until the day we die? <br><br>Most people, hopefully you too, have noted that the writers of the New Testament seem to put different emphasis on the role of works in &quot;being&quot; saved. Paul talks about it in Romans and Galatians. James said show your faith by your works.</span>
