        June 8, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by NightSpirit</div><br><br>Briefly, there are different beliefs on whether salvation is a one time done deal or whether it is a continuing process, whether one can be lost again after coming to believe in Christ.<br><br>In my own personal experience, there have been times that I left the church and left off practicing my faith, even to the point of living sinfully. Not something I'm proud of but it happened. I never felt Jesus left me during those times, though and I've been brought back more than once, even closer to him, like the lamb He left the flock to find and then put on his shoulders in Luke 15. Maybe we <i>can</i> utterly forsake Him but I tend to lean toward the idea that once we are born again, we are His family and He doesn't let us go so easily.</blockquote><br><br>I think it's a bit of both. I have had your same experience, where each time I would leave Christianity, my time away from it would get shorter and shorter each time. Last time it was only about three months before I was feeling that pull back.<br><br>Jesus says that no one can come to him unless the Father draws in that person.<br><br><blockquote>John 6:44 (NAB)<br><br>[44]*No one can come to me unless the Father who sent me draw him, and I will raise him on the last day.<br><br>John 6:65 (NAB)<br><br>[65]*And he said, “For this reason I have told you that no one can come to me unless it is granted him by my Father.”<br></blockquote><br><br>So maybe once God selects us, and he knows that we are capable of knowing the truth and serving him, well he doesn't let go so easily? What rule free will plays in this, I'm not sure. I'm sure one could continue to ignore that pulling back to God, but I think one would then become unhappy and lost.</span>
