        June 8, 2009<br><br><blockquote><div>Originally Posted by NightSpirit</div><br><br>People outside of the Christian experience have the wrong notion that we have read a book with a shaky historical foundation and were convinced to  try to adhere to the book to be &quot;saved&quot;, out of fear of hell or because of tradition. There is so much more to it than that. <br><br>Most of us have that experience, that acceptance of who Jesus is and an awareness of God's love for us, usually before we have even read the whole Bible. We can come to believe either as a result of hearing a sermon or from testimony from another Christian, even from a dream or vision. After we receive His Spirit and He begins to teach us, we believe more of the Bible because what is written there happens or begins to happen in us.    <br><br>I know this. I know God is my Father and Jesus is His Son who took away the sins of the world, mine included. And when I read it there in the Bible, I knew the Apostle and I had an experience with the same God. <br><br>We all may not know the whole Bible yet and our habits may not change as quickly as our desire to be like Jesus. We may need counsel or help from other Christians or a priest or pastor. But because Jesus is the author and finisher of our faith, we can sense He is with us.</blockquote><br><br>I totally agree. It's always weird to hear people say that we believe out of fear, because that is the furthest thing from the truth. I believe because I have experienced God. I know him as a loving father and protector, very merciful yet just.<br><br>I actually don't really think people who are ignorant of the truth will go to hell. I don't think God will let go of people that easily. I think that God's commandments are written in our hearts, and some people still follow them even if they aren't Christian. For others, well I think God tries to reach us all in some way. We just have to be open.</span>
