        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: NightSpirit</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 8, 2009<br><br>People outside of the Christian experience have the wrong notion that we have read a book with a shaky historical foundation and were convinced to  try to adhere to the book to be &quot;saved&quot;, out of fear of hell or because of tradition. There is so much more to it than that. <br><br>Most of us have that experience, that acceptance of who Jesus is and an awareness of God's love for us, usually before we have even read the whole Bible. We can come to believe either as a result of hearing a sermon or from testimony from another Christian, even from a dream or vision. After we receive His Spirit and He begins to teach us, we believe more of the Bible because what is written there happens or begins to happen in us.<br><br><blockquote>Romans 8 - For as many as are led by the Spirit of God, they are the sons of God.  For ye have not received the spirit of bondage again to fear; but ye have received the Spirit of adoption, whereby we cry, Abba, Father.  The Spirit itself beareth witness with our spirit, that we are the children of God:</blockquote><br><br>I know this. I know God is my Father and Jesus is His Son who took away the sins of the world, mine included. And when I read it there in the Bible, I knew the Apostle and I had an experience with the same God. <br><br>We all may not know the whole Bible yet and our habits may not change as quickly as our desire to be like Jesus. We may need counsel or help from other Christians or a priest or pastor. But because Jesus is the author and finisher of our faith, we can sense He is with us. <br><br>When He ministered here on earth, Jesus didn't speak so much about specific sins, especially to the prostitutes, thieves, drunkards and such. He said He wasn't sent to condemn. &quot;Go your way and sin no more, neither do I condemn you, those who are forgiven much, love much, etc.&quot; He told us that neither sin nor holiness originates from the outside but from within. That's where He starts with us knowing that what's in our heart will come out our mouth and manifest in our lives. (Matthew 15, Mark 7). <br><br>Briefly, there are different beliefs on whether salvation is a one time done deal or whether it is a continuing process, whether one can be lost again after coming to believe in Christ. <br><br>In my own personal experience, there have been times that I left the church and left off practicing my faith, even to the point of living sinfully. Not something I'm proud of but it happened. I never felt Jesus left me during those times, though and I've been brought back more than once, even closer to him, like the lamb He left the flock to find and then put on his shoulders in Luke 15. Maybe we <i>can</i> utterly forsake Him but I tend to lean toward the idea that once we are born again, we are His family and He doesn't let us go so easily.</span>
