        <span class="author" style="text-align:left;"><strong>by: NightSpirit</strong></span><br>
        <br><span class="subBodyText">
        June 8, 2009<br><br>Just FYI, but there is actually some resistance within non-Catholic circles to the label &quot;protestant.&quot; It really no longer applies as a descriptive term since we are so far removed from 1529 and most Christians are not really protesting the Catholic church or anything for that matter. <br><br>It does seem to be a little of a divisive term but that's just human, I guess. One of the churches I used to attend changed it's name recently from &quot;full gospel.&quot; I don't know why they did it but that's another possibly divisive term, implying by the distinction that other churches are following &quot;less than&quot; the full gospel.  <br><br>There do still exist churches that are proud of the Protestant label, (just like some southerners still call themselves rebels) and feel it's their duty to &quot;protest&quot; Catholic doctrine. To those denominations, because of a limited understanding of the true faith most Catholics have in Jesus, a person is considered either Catholic or Christian, but not both, to imply that Catholics don't know Christ.<br><br>As related to the OP, those attitudes mostly come from differences in beliefs of who has really met the qualifications to be called &quot;saved.&quot; To be able to pinpoint a definite day when we came to understand and believe, to know a change took place, with a baptism following, is required for salvation to some  fundamental &quot;protestant&quot; churches.  <br><br>I don't think the Bible specifies whether salvation has to happen instantly or whether we can also come to believe gradually, through observations and studying the Bible. At some point we do have to become aware of our sins and turn to Jesus for forgiveness.  We do have to believe what the Holy Spirit is speaking to our hearts about Jesus, as the Christ and God's Son, and believe it enough to speak it. Trying to put that miracle into a formula is where I think our traditions get in the way and cause doubts and unneccesary burdens for people.</span>
